President Obama spoke with President Ellen Johnson Sirleaf of Liberia and President Ernest Bai Koroma of Sierra Leone regarding the Ebola outbreak in West Africa. The President expressed the commitment of the United States to work with Liberia, Sierra Leone, and other international partners to contain the outbreak. He also offered condolences for the lives lost. The leaders discussed ongoing mitigation measures, including those directed through the U.S. Disaster Assistance Response Team and personnel deployed from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. President Obama appreciated President Sirleaf and President Koroma's decisions to forgo the U.S.-Africa Leaders Summit to tend to the outbreak.